maml:description.maml:para: Establishes initial connection to Palo Alto API.

The Get-PaDevice cmdlet establishes and validates connection parameters to allow further communications to the Palo Alto API. The cmdlet needs at least two parameters: - The device IP address or FQDN - A valid API key or PSCredential object
The cmdlet returns an object containing details of the connection, but this can be discarded or saved as desired; the returned object is not necessary to provide to further calls to the API.

maml:Description.maml:para: Fully-qualified domain name for the Palo Alto Device. Don't include the protocol ("https://" or "http://").
ApiKey used to access Palo Alto Device.
The port the Palo Alto Device is using for management communicatins. This defaults to port 443 over HTTPS, and port 80 over HTTP.
When specified, configures the API connection to run over HTTP rather than the default HTTPS. Not recommended!
When used, the cmdlet returns nothing on success.
When used, all certificate warnings are ignored.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Get-PaDevice -DeviceAddress "pa.example.com" -ApiKey "LUFRPT1asdfPR2JtSDl5M2tjfdsaTktBeTkyaGZMTURasdfTTU9BZm89OGtKN0F"

dev:remarks.maml:para: Connects to Palo Alto Device using the default port (443) over SSL (HTTPS) using an API Key

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 2 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Get-PaDevice -DeviceAddress "pa.example.com" -Credential (Get-Credential)

dev:remarks.maml:para: Prompts the user for username and password and connects to the Palo Alto Device with those creds. This will generate a keygen call and the user's API Key will be used for all subsequent calls.
